I don&#39;t think it breaks LSP.  The base class is TestCase (through
AbstractEnhancedTextfieldTest), the derived classes are your specific
test cases.  They all act the same and their clients never know the
difference.  Yes, if you create a new component you will have to add
that component to the abstract test case.  So what?  Nothing comes for
free...  But, once it&#39;s added in, it is tested the same and thus your
ROI is extraordinarily positive!  About coupling -- don&#39;t worry, your
test cases ought to be coupled to your tested objects!  If they aren&#39;t,
they aren&#39;t really test cases.  Or did I miss something?

FWIW: I don&#39;t worry too much about &quot;good design&quot;, inheritance,
polymorphism, etc. in my test cases.  I use it when I can see clearly
that it will save me time (and most often I refactor toward it)! 
Otherwise they are generally pretty flat.  Obviously, that doesn&#39;t apply
to the testing framework itself!!!!

=jason

